==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*setla-'', representing Indo-European ''*sed-lo-'', from ''*sed-'' ‘sit’.  Cognate with Old High German [[sezzal]] (German [[Sessel]]), Middle Dutch [[setel|sētel]] (Dutch [[zetel]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌹𐍄𐌻𐍃]].  The Indo-European root is also the source of Greek [[ἑλλά]], Latin [[sella]], Russian [[седло]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/setl/}}

===Noun===
'''setl''' ''n'' (plural '''[[setlu]]''')
# [[sitting]], [[residence]]
# [[seat]], [[bench]], [[throne]]
# [[setting]] (of sun etc.)

